Interpret the slope For every additional year of education, our income will be increased by $898.8, on average

(f).

Interpret the intercept The intercept may not have a practical meaning since it indicates that if you have 0 education you have negative income.

(g).

It appears as if the outliers are causing the normality assumption to be violated.

It appears the assumption of the errors having constant variance is not met because of some outliers.

Code Appendix

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE)
library(car)
summary(Prestige)
plot(Prestige$education, Prestige$income, main = "Scatterplot of Education and Income", xlab = "Years of Education", ylab = "Income")
{plot(Prestige$education, Prestige$income, main = "Scatterplot of Education and Income", xlab = "Years of Education", ylab = "Income")
#skeleton : lm (Y ~ X, data = data)
the.model = lm(income ~ education, data = Prestige)
#intercept = B0
#slope = B1
abline(the.model, col = "blue")}
{hist(the.model$residuals)
qqnorm(the.model$residuals)
qqline(the.model$residuals)}
#checks ()
#if follows line it is normal
{plot(the.model$fitted.values, the.model$residuals, xlab = "residuals", ylab = "fitted values")
abline(h = 0, col = "blue")}

# X = 1:200
# Y = rnorm(200)
# hist(Y)
# qqnorm(Y)
# qqline(Y)
# plot(Y)
#normal data should look like that
#summary(the.model)
confint(the.model, level = 0.95)
